
What is EKS?
Amazon EKS is a managed Kubernetes service.

AWS manages:
Kubernetes Control Plane
High Availability
Security Patches

You manage:
Worker Nodes
Applications

Why Kubernetes?
Imagine:
50 Containers
100 Containers
500 Containers

Managing manually becomes impossible.

Kubernetes automates:

Deployment
Scaling
Self Healing
Load Balancing

EKS Architecture:
Users
   ↓
Load Balancer
   ↓
EKS Cluster
   ↓
Worker Nodes
   ↓
Pods

Kubernetes Components:

Pod:
Smallest deployable unit.

Pod
 ↓
Container

Deployment:
Manages pods.

Example:
Desired Pods = 3
One Pod Fails
New Pod Created

Service:
Exposes application.
Users
  ↓
Service
  ↓
Pods

Node:
Worker machine running pods.

Real-Time Scenario:
Netflix-like Streaming Platform

Users
   ↓
ALB
   ↓
EKS Cluster
   ↓
100+ Pods
   ↓
Microservices

Services:

Authentication
Payments
Videos
Recommendations
Notifications

Each service runs independently.

Benefits:
Self Healing
Pod Crash
    ↓
New Pod Created

Auto Scaling:
Traffic Increase
      ↓
More Pods

Rolling Updates:
Version 1
     ↓
Version 2

Without downtime.

Interview Questions:
What is a Pod?
Smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes containing one or more containers.

What is a Deployment?
Object used to manage pods and maintain desired state.
